\emph default
 (SDE) has long been thought of as a veterinary pathogen, but evidence has
 emerged that it can cause serious and life-threatening human diseases tradition
ally associated with SPY.
 Because they cohabit the same ecological niche, genetic exchanges between
 SPY and SDE are likely.
 In this study we explored patterns of recombination in these species, as
 well as duplication, loss, and transfer of their genes.
 We attempted to address a question of whether genetic exchanges between
 SPY and SDE could have played a role in the formation of pathogenicity
 of SDE.
 Previous studies were limited to relatively small portion of a genome partly
 because of lack of methods for studying bacterial recombination on the
 genome scale, and partly due to unavailability of relevant bacterial genomes.
 The results allowed us to create a map of relative recombination rates
 across most of parts of the genomes of the species.
 We observed high variation in the recombination rates, including several
 loci which appeared to be hotspots for bacterial recombination.
 We found marginally supporting evidence that there appeared to be relatively
 more genomic flow from SPY to SDE than in the other direction based on
 bacterial recombination as surrogate measure of genomic flow.
 Reconciliation of species tree and gene trees based on gene fragments provided
 evidence that virulence genes appeared to undergo horizontal gene transfer
 than non-virulence genes.
 On the contrary, genomic flow due to bacterial recombination was not found
 to be associated with virulence genes.
 This might indicate that additional genes obtained via horizontal gene
 transfer were more effective than gene fragments transfer via bacterial
 recombination for pathogenic bacteria to acquire biological functions that
 were critical to their survival in the environment in which their close
 relatives thrived.
