\begin_layout Standard
Bacteria evolve vertically and horizontally.
 Vertically, bacteria evolve clonally: parents pass their genetic contents
 down to their daughter cells.
 Mutations during the vertical evolution accumulate, which allows bacterial
 species to diverge in their genomic contents.
 Horizontally, bacteria obtain parts of genomes from others via conjugation
 by plasmid, transduction by bacteriophages, or transformation of naked
 DNA uptake 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Thomas2005"

\end_inset

.
 Acquired DNAs can either replace their indigenous homologs, or be added
 to their recipient bacterial genomes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g.,"
key "Lawrence2009"

\end_inset

.
 The former process involves bacterial recombination, and the latter horizontal
 transfer of DNA fragments.
 We wish to ditinguish gene transfer due to bacterial homologous recombination
 from additional gene fragments to a recipient bacterium due to horizontal
 gene transfer.
 Note that we discriminate between the two processes throughout the manuscript.
 Both of the processes result in gene transfer from a donor to a recipient.
 Genes are presumed to be parts of regions of a genome not necessarily protein-c
oding DNAs.
 New functions of bacteria appear to emerge more easily in horizontal way
 than in vertical way.
 When one species of bacteria thrives in its environment and another relatively
 close species starts to cohabit with the indigenous species, some genetic
 elements in one of the two species would benefit another species.
 If the two species do not compete with each other, then the increased genetic
 variation from multiple species would eventually bring advantage to both
 of the species.
 Pathogenicity of bacteria should be no exception.
 Studying pathogenic gene flow should shed light on the etiology of the
 bacterial pathogens.
 
